{
  "comment_text": {
    "snp1.8:1.1": "See <a href='https://suttacentral.net/an5.169/en/sujato#3.1'>AN 5.169:3.1</a> for this sense of <i lang='pi' translate='no'>atthakusala</i>. | <i lang='pi' translate='no'>Kusala</i> in the sense of “one who is skilled”, an “expert” is found occasionally in the canon, especially in the Aṭṭhakavagga. It appears also in early Sanskrit, for example, for those who are “skilled” in recitation (Chāndogya Upaniṣad 1.8.1), or for those who only think that they are skilled (Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa 11.4.2.1, 4, and 13). ",
    "snp1.8:1.2": "Reading the absolutive in an infinitive sense, an alternative given in the commentary: <i lang='pi' translate='no'>abhisamecca viharitukāmena</i>. ",
    "snp1.8:3.2": "Compare <a href='https://suttacentral.net/an4.121/en/sujato#3.3'>AN 4.121:3.3</a>. ",
    "snp1.8:4.3": "Creatures “firm and frail” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>tasathāvare</i>) is a common Jain idiom (eg. Uttarādhyayana 5.8: <i lang='pi' translate='no'>tasesu thāvaresu ya</i>; Sūyagaḍa 3.4.20: <i lang='pi' translate='no'>je keī tasathāvarā</i>; Dasaveyāliya 4.1.42: <i lang='pi' translate='no'>tasaṁ vā thāvaraṁ vā</i>; Ācāraṅgasūtra 9.1.14: <i lang='pi' translate='no'>tasa-jīvā ya thāvarattāe</i>). ",
    "snp1.8:5.3": "For “have become or will be” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>bhūtā va sambhavesī va</i>) I follow Norman and Bodhi in reading <i lang='pi' translate='no'>sambhavesī</i> as a future active participle. Compare such Sanskrit constructions as Rig Veda 1.66.8, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>yamo ha jāto yamo janitvaṁ</i> (“the twin that is born and the twin about to be born”) and Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa 2.3.1.24, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>bhūtaṁ caiva bhaviṣyacca jātaṁ ca janiṣyamāṇaṁ</i> (“has become and will be, born and to be born”). ",
    "snp1.8:6.1": "",
    "snp1.8:10.1": "The final verse is set in a different meter, and given that the preceding verse already brings the poem to a satisfying conclusion, must be a later addition. Apparently the original poem was not Buddhist enough, and at some point more doctrinal material was felt to be needed. ",
    "snp1.8:10.4": "Note that <i lang='pi' translate='no'>jātu</i> here is not connected to <i lang='pi' translate='no'>jāti</i> “birth”. Rather, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>na hi jātu</i> is an idiom meaning “never”. Commentary: <i lang='pi' translate='no'>ekaṁseneva</i>. "
  },
